---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Setup" description="Create the project folder, open VS Code, launch Claude, and hand over the project files.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Setup</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">Before you can direct Claude through tickets, you need to set up the workspace. This is the same process for every project in the course. About 10 minutes.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-3">Step 1: Create your project folder</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">Open any terminal. Create a folder for this project inside <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">~/dev</code> (you'll use this parent folder for every project in the course):</p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ mkdir -p ~/dev && cd ~/dev
$ mkdir your-project-name && cd your-project-name`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">Replace <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">your-project-name</code> with whatever the project is called — check the landing page for the name. By the end of the course, <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">~/dev</code> will contain 6 project folders.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-3 mt-8">Step 2: Open VS Code</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">Open the folder in VS Code — this is where you'll do all your work:</p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ code .`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">VS Code opens with the project folder in the sidebar. You'll see files appear here in real time as Claude creates them.</p>

  <details class="mb-6 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>New to VS Code?</summary>
    <div class="p-4 space-y-2">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary"><strong>Sidebar (left):</strong> Shows your project files. Click any file to view it.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary"><strong>Editor (centre):</strong> Where file contents appear. You won't edit files directly — Claude does that — but you'll read them here.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary"><strong>Terminal (bottom):</strong> This is where you'll run Claude. Open it with <strong>Ctrl+`</strong> (backtick) or <strong>View → Terminal</strong> from the menu.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">See the <a href="https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/getstarted/userinterface">VS Code interface guide</a> for a visual overview.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <h2 class="mb-3 mt-8">Step 3: Open the terminal in VS Code</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">Press <strong>Ctrl+`</strong> (backtick — the key above Tab) to open the built-in terminal. This terminal runs inside VS Code, so you can see files and the terminal at the same time.</p>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2"><strong>Important:</strong> Make sure the terminal is in the right folder:</p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ pwd`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">It should show a path ending in your project folder name. If it doesn't:</p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ cd ~/dev/your-project-name`}</CodeBlock>

  <details class="mb-6 mt-4 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>Can't find the backtick key?</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Use the menu instead: <strong>View → Terminal</strong>. Or press <strong>Cmd+Shift+P</strong> (Mac) / <strong>Ctrl+Shift+P</strong> (Windows/Linux), type "terminal", and select "Toggle Terminal".</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <h2 class="mb-3 mt-8">Step 4: Launch Claude Code</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">In the VS Code terminal:</p>
  <CodeBlock terminal copy>{`$ claude`}</CodeBlock>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>First time launching Claude Code?</strong> The very first time you run <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">claude</code>, it will open your browser to authenticate — log in with your Claude account. After that, each time you launch Claude in a new project folder, it will ask you to <strong>trust the folder</strong> and the <strong>authors</strong>. This is a safety feature — Claude Code can read and modify files in the folder, so it wants your explicit permission. Say yes to both. You'll only need to do this once per project.</p>
  </Callout>

  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4 mb-4">Once you're in, you're talking to your AI developer. Watch the sidebar on the left — you'll see files appear as Claude creates them.</p>

  <Callout variant="warning">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>GitHub permissions:</strong> Claude will also need to create repositories, Issues, and PRs on your behalf. The first time it tries, your terminal may prompt you to authorise GitHub access — follow the prompts. If you run into issues, check that <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">gh auth status</code> shows you're logged in.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-3 mt-8">Step 5: Give Claude the project files</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-2">Claude needs two things to get started: the CLAUDE.md (project memory) and the BACKLOG.md (tickets). Go to the project's architecture page and backlog page, copy each using the copy buttons, and paste them to Claude:</p>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`Here's the CLAUDE.md for the project:

[Paste CLAUDE.md here]

And here's the BACKLOG.md:

[Paste BACKLOG.md here]`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4 mb-2">Claude reads both files and now understands the full project — what to build, how to build it, and what the acceptance criteria are for every ticket.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-3 mt-8">Step 6: Start Ticket 1</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-2">Every project's first ticket is setup — creating the repo, installing dependencies, verifying the dev server starts. Tell Claude:</p>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`Start Ticket 1.`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">That's it. Claude reads the CLAUDE.md and BACKLOG.md, sees what Ticket 1 requires, and does it. Watch the sidebar — files will start appearing.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-3 mt-8">Step 7: Verify</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">Once Claude finishes Ticket 1, check the result against the acceptance criteria in the backlog. For a setup ticket, this usually means:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-4">
    <li>Does the dev server start? (Run the dev command from the Makefile)</li>
    <li>Does the page load in the browser?</li>
    <li>Are the expected files present in the sidebar?</li>
    <li>Is the GitHub repo created with Issues and a project board?</li>
  </ul>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Ticket 1 complete.</strong> You directed Claude to set up project infrastructure and verified the result. The skill here was communication: clear instructions and verification against specific expectations. Now move on to your first real build ticket.</p>
  </Callout>

  <!-- VS Code Tips -->
  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-12">VS Code tips</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">You'll be spending a lot of time in VS Code. A few things that help:</p>

  <div class="space-y-3 mb-6">
    <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
      <span class="text-primary font-bold mt-0.5">1</span>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary"><strong class="text-text">Ctrl+` (backtick)</strong> — toggle the terminal open and closed. You'll use this constantly.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
      <span class="text-primary font-bold mt-0.5">2</span>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary"><strong class="text-text">Cmd+P (Mac) / Ctrl+P (Windows)</strong> — quick open. Type a filename to jump to it instantly.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
      <span class="text-primary font-bold mt-0.5">3</span>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary"><strong class="text-text">Cmd+Shift+P / Ctrl+Shift+P</strong> — command palette. Search for any VS Code action.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
      <span class="text-primary font-bold mt-0.5">4</span>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary"><strong class="text-text">Split the view</strong> — drag a file tab to the right side of the editor to see two files at once. Useful for comparing Claude's output to the design spec.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <details class="mb-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>Ask Claude to set up useful extensions</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-2">After setup, you can ask Claude:</p>
      <CodeBlock copy>{`What VS Code extensions would be useful for this project? Install the ones that help with development.`}</CodeBlock>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-2">Claude will suggest and install extensions relevant to your tech stack. These give you autocomplete and error highlighting — helpful for reading Claude's code.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: development tools</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">Your editor and AI tools shape how you work. Here's what exists beyond what we use in this project.</p>

      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-text mb-3">IDEs</p>
      <div class="space-y-3 mb-6">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">VS Code</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">What we use. Free, extensible, dominant market share. Most tutorials and extensions target VS Code.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Cursor</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">VS Code fork with deep AI integration. AI autocomplete and chat built into the editor.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">JetBrains (WebStorm, IntelliJ, PyCharm)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Professional IDEs with deep language support. Popular in enterprise. Paid, but free for students.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Neovim / Vim</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Terminal-based editors. Steep learning curve, extremely fast once mastered. Used by some senior developers.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-text mb-3">AI developer tools</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Claude Code</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">What we use. CLI-based, agentic. Reads your project, writes code, opens PRs.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">GitHub Copilot</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">AI autocomplete in your editor. Suggests code as you type. Different model: assists line-by-line rather than directing whole features.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">ChatGPT / Claude (chat interface)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Browser-based AI chat. Good for planning, brainstorming, generating templates. We use this for PRD and design spec generation from Project 3 onwards.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">v0 (Vercel)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">AI UI generation. Describe a component, get React/Tailwind code. Useful for rapid prototyping.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">We use VS Code + Claude Code because they're the most capable combination for directing AI to build full features. In a team, you'll encounter different editors and AI tools. The directing skill — clear instructions, thorough verification — works with all of them.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
</DocsLayout>
